# Salesforce CMS Content Import

## Zip Structure

Each content item is a folder containing two files. Folders are nested under a CMS folder name:

```
CMS Folder Name/
  UniqueFolder001/
    content.json
    _meta.json
  UniqueFolder002/
    content.json
    _meta.json
```

Zip the top-level folder(s) directly — the zip root should contain the CMS folder name directory.

## content.json

```json
{
  "type" : "your_content_type_developer_name",
  "title" : "Human-readable title",
  "contentBody" : {
    "nameField" : "Value for the NAMEFIELD node",
    "richTextField" : "<p>HTML content for RTE nodes</p>",
    "textField" : "Plain text value"
  },
  "urlName" : "url-slug-with-hyphens"
}
```

- `type` must match the `developerName` of a ManagedContentType deployed to the org **and enabled on the CMS workspace**.
- `contentBody` keys must match the `nodeName` values from the content type definition.
- RTE fields use raw HTML (not unicode-escaped). Write files with UTF-8 no-BOM encoding.
- `urlName` is the URL slug — lowercase, hyphens allowed.
- Optional fields from the content type can be omitted.

## _meta.json

```json
{
  "apiName" : "unique_api_name",
  "path" : "CMS Folder Name",
  "taxonomyTerms" : [ ]
}
```

- `apiName`: **Only** alphanumeric characters and underscores. No hyphens, no spaces. Must begin with a letter, not end with underscore, no consecutive underscores. Must be unique per content type.
- `path`: The CMS folder the item belongs to. Must match the folder directory name in the zip.
- **Do NOT include `contentKey`** — Salesforce auto-generates it on import.

## Common Errors

| Error | Cause | Fix |
|-------|-------|-----|
| "couldn't find a content.json file" | Wrong filename or not inside a folder | Each item needs its own subfolder with `content.json` inside |
| "Specify value for type property" | Content type not recognized | Ensure the type is deployed AND enabled on the CMS workspace |
| "This field can contain only underscores and alphanumeric characters" | `apiName` has hyphens or special chars | Use underscores only: `my_api_name` not `my-api-name` |
| "Invalid value for ContentKey" | Made-up contentKey format | Omit `contentKey` entirely — let Salesforce generate it |

## Build Script Pattern (PowerShell)

Use `[System.IO.File]::WriteAllText()` with `UTF8Encoding($false)` (no BOM) to avoid PowerShell's `ConvertTo-Json` unicode-escaping HTML `<>` characters:

```powershell
function Write-JsonFile($path, $jsonString) {
    [System.IO.File]::WriteAllText($path, $jsonString, [System.Text.UTF8Encoding]::new($false))
}
```

Build JSON via here-strings (`@' ... '@`) to preserve raw HTML, then zip with `Compress-Archive`.

## Post-Import

After importing, content items are in **draft** status. They must be **published** in the CMS workspace before they are available to LWC wire adapters like `getContents` from `experience/cmsDeliveryApi`.
